  <p>The <a href=3D"https://www.nist.gov/si-redefinition/kelvin-introductio=
n">kelvin</a> (K) is defined by taking the fixed numerical value of the Bol=
tzmann constant k to be 1.380 649 =C3=9710<sup>=E2=88=9223</sup> when expre=
ssed in the unit J K<sup>=E2=88=921</sup>, which is equal to kg m<sup>2</su=
p> s<sup>=E2=88=922</sup> K<sup>=E2=88=921</sup>, where the kilogram, meter=
 and second are defined in terms of h, c and =E2=88=86=CE=BD<sub>Cs</sub>. =
The temperature 0 K is commonly referred to as "absolute zero." On the wide=
ly used Celsius temperature scale, water freezes at 0 =C2=B0C and boils at =
about 100 =C2=B0C. One Celsius degree is an interval of 1 K, and zero degre=
es Celsius is 273.15 K. An interval of one Celsius degree corresponds to an=
 interval of 1.8 Fahrenheit degrees on the Fahrenheit temperature scale.</p=
><p>The standard temperature at the triple point of water is provided by a =
special cell, an evacuated glass cylinder containing pure water. When the c=
ell is cooled enough so that a mantle of ice forms around the reentrant wel=
l, the temperature at the interface of solid, liquid, and vapor is 273.16 K=
. Thermometers to be calibrated are placed in the reentrant well.</p>=20
